alth.pa.gov/topics/disease/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx Coronavirus information] from the [[Pennsylvania Department of Health]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2020 in Pennsylvania|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Health in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Pennsylvania, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania\n| image           = Pennsylvania National Guard - 49686952447.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = [[Pennsylvania Air National Guard]] troops set up at a Montgomery County coronavirus test site\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak Pennsylvania per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 inhabitants by county\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware]] and [[Wayne County, Pennsylvania|Wayne]] counties\n| arrival_date    = March 6, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=6|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| date            = \n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 24,199\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 524\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.health.pa.gov/topics/disease/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[U.S. state]] of [[Pennsylvania]] in March 2020. As of April 12, 2020, the [[Pennsylvania Department of Health]] has confirmed 24,199 cases and 524 deaths in the state.<ref>https://www.health.pa.gov/topics/disease/coronavirus/Pages/Cases.aspx</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Pennsylvania medical cases chart}}\n{{seealso|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Philadelphia}}\n*On March 6, Governor [[Tom Wolf]] reported Pennsylvania's first two confirmed cases of [[COVID-19]] in [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware County]] and in [[Wayne County, Pennsylvania|Wayne County]].<ref>{{Cite press release|date=March 6, 2020|title=Wolf Administration Confirms Two Presumptive Positive Cases of COVID-19|agency=[[Pennsylvania]] Office of the Governor|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/wolf-administration-confirms-two-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19/|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307002100/https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/wolf-administration-confirms-two-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=2 presumed positive coronavirus cases in Pa., including Delaware County|publisher=[[WPVI-TV|WPVI]]|url=https://6abc.com/5990338/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306220251/https://6abc.com/5990338/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Both cases were related to travel.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=Pennsylvania now has 2 confirmed cases of coronavirus|work=[[Associated Press|AP]] via [[WHYY-TV|WHYY]]|url=https://whyy.org/articles/pennsylvania-now-has-2-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307142840/https://whyy.org/articles/pennsylvania-now-has-2-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=Pa. confirms 'presumed positive' cases of the coronavirus|last=Parker|first=Randy|work=[[York Daily Record]]|url=https://www.ydr.com/story/news/2020/03/06/coronavirus-in-pa-first-covid-19-case-confirmed-in-pennsylvania-wayne-delaware-county/4966026002/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307091047/https://www.ydr.com/story/news/2020/03/06/coronavirus-in-pa-first-covid-19-case-confirmed-in-pennsylvania-wayne-delaware-county/4966026002/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=Pennsylvania Reports 2 Coronavirus Cases, 1 in Delaware County |last=Stamm|first=Dan|publisher=[[WCAU-TV]] |url=https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/pennsylvania-reports-2-coronavirus-cases-1-in-delaware-county/2317204}}</ref> \n*On March 9, 4 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 10.\n*On March 10, 2 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wesa.fm/post/live-blog-coronavirus-pittsburgh-march-9-15|title=LIVE BLOG: Coronavirus In Pittsburgh, March 9\u201315|last=Staff|first=WESA|website=www.wesa.fm|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*On March 13, Governor Wolf announced that all Pennsylvania schools will be closed for at least two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/pennsylvania-schools-closed-coronavirus/2325564/?amp |title=Pennsylvania, Delaware Close All Schools Due to Outbreak |publisher=[[WCAU]] |date= |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, park programs were canceled.<ref>[https://www.poconorecord.com/news/20200314/pa-cancels-public-park-programs-in-light-of-covid-19 PA cancels public park programs in light of COVID-19] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314144712/https://www.poconorecord.com/news/20200314/pa-cancels-public-park-programs-in-light-of-covid-19 |date=March 14, 2020 }} Pocono Record</ref>\n*By March 17, there were 96 cases in the state; more than half of them were in the [[Philadelphia]] area with [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]] as the highest number.<ref name=\"6abc31520\" />\n*On March 18, the [[Pennsylvania Department of Health|department of health]] reported the state's first death related to the virus, a patient at [[St. Luke's University Health Network|St. Luke's]] Fountain Hill campus in [[Northampton County, Pennsylvania|Northampton County]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.pa.gov/topics/disease/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx|title=Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=PA Department of Health|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/1st-coronavirus-death-in-pennsylvania-is-from-lehigh-valley.html|title=1st coronavirus death in Pennsylvania is from Lehigh Valley|last=lehighvalleylive.com|first=Steve Novak {{!}} For|date=2020-03-18|website=lehighvalleylive|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210846/https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/1st-coronavirus-death-in-pennsylvania-is-from-lehigh-valley.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March 18, there are 133 cases in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtae.com/article/coronavirus-cases-in-pennsylvania/31291493|title=First coronavirus death reported in Pennsylvania; 133 cases total reported statewide|date=2020-03-19|website=WTAE|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084041/https://www.wtae.com/article/coronavirus-cases-in-pennsylvania/31291493|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On March 19, Governor Wolf ordered a statewide shutdown of all \"non-life sustaining businesses,\" with enforcement of this order going into effect at 12:01&nbsp;am on Saturday, March 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/all-non-life-sustaining-businesses-in-pennsylvania-to-close-physical-locations-as-of-8-pm-today-to-slow-spread-of-covid-19/|title=ALL NON-LIFE-SUSTAINING BUSINESSES IN PENNSYLVANIA TO CLOSE PHYSICAL LOCATIONS AS OF 8 PM TODAY TO SLOW SPREAD OF COVID-19|date=2020-03-19|website=Governor Tom Wolf|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320184236/https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/all-non-life-sustaining-businesses-in-pennsylvania-to-close-physical-locations-as-of-8-pm-today-to-slow-spread-of-covid-19/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The [[Pennsylvania Department of Education|PA Department of Education]] canceled all statewide assessments including the PSSA testing, Keystone exams, and the Pennsylvania Alternate System of Assessment (PASA) for the remainder of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-latest-pennsylvania-department-of-education-cancels-statewide-assessments/|title=Coronavirus Latest: Pennsylvania Department Of Education Cancels Statewide Assessments|date=2020-03-19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319214719/https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-latest-pennsylvania-department-of-education-cancels-statewide-assessments/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On March 21, the department of health announced the state's second death as well as 103 new cases. The second death was in [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Allegheny County]].<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Rachel Levine]], the Secretary of Health for the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, said during a press conference \"A state-wide shelter in place was not out of the question.\"<ref name=\"Levine\">{{Cite web|url=https://papost.org/2020/03/19/who-is-rachel-levine-pa-health-secretary-offers-calm-reassurance-amid-pandemic/|title=Who is Rachel Levine? Pa. health secretary offers calm, reassurance amid pandemic|date=2020-03-19|website=PA Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n*On March 22, 273 new cases were reported, bringing the total to 644. The sixth death occurred in Montgomery County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wpxi.com/news/top-stories/live-updates-coronavirus-pennsylvania-what-you-need-know-monday/OWEEFQQCDVG4DDVQQLDGAYSJPA/|title=LIVE UPDATES: Coronavirus in Pa.: Stay-at-home order issued for Allegheny Co. as amount of cases across state rises to 644|last=Staff|first=WPXI com News|website=WPXI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wpxi.com/news/top-stories/live-updates-coronavirus-pennsylvania-what-you-need-know-sunday/VHACVFVHCJD5HMAKLZNQB4NPZE/|title=TIMELINE: Pennsylvania coronavirus updates March 22|last=Staff|first=WPXI com News|website=WPXI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*On March 25, A 35-year-old woman in [[Hanover Township, Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Hanover Township, Luzerne County]] was arrested for deliberately coughing and spitting on food at a Gerrity's supermarket. She made verbal threats about being infected with Covid-19 and has been charged with two counts of terrorism and two other felonies plus a misdemeanor for attempting to steal a pack of beer. The supermarket had to throw out $35,000 worth of merchandise and has since raised employee pay $1 per hour. The woman is being tested for coronavirus.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/grocery-store-throws-35k-worth-141700713.html Woman who coughed on $35K worth of grocery store food faces felony charges] by Elisha Fieldstadt, NBC News, 27 March 2020</ref>\n*On March 28, Governor Tom Wolf issued a stay-at-home order for Beaver, Butler, Westmoreland, Centre, and Washington Counties, according to a release from Harrisburg. Governor Wolf announced 533 new cases, bringing the statewide total to 2,751. The highest rise in cases was in [[Philadelphia County, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia County]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n*On April 1, Governor Wolf extended the stay-at-home order across the entire state effective that evening at 8:00 pm.\n*On April 3, Governor Wolf asked Pennsylvanians to wear cloth face coverings in public. Philadelphia reduced recycling pickup to every two weeks due to staff shortages.<ref>[https://whyy.org/articles/coronavirus-update-15000-chromebooks-donated-to-phillys-charter-catholic-schools/ Coronavirus update: Gov. Tom Wolf asks Pennsylvanians to wear masks outdoors]</ref>\n*On April 9, Governor Wolf has officially ordered the closing of all Pennsylvania schools through the end of the academic school year. He stated that they will resume all classes through means of Google Classroom and other online classroom tools. He has not yet stated if the Class of 2020 graduations will be postponed or cancelled.<ref>https://www.wpxi.com/news/pennsylvania/schools-ordered/X4MKTVHMR6UKVL2XSJIFNVHLQE/</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:20200317TLASouthSt.jpg|thumb|left|The TLA on March 17, 2020 during the City of Philadelphia's shutdown during the Coronavirus epidemic]]\nAs a result of the coronavirus pandemic, Governor Wolf has implemented [[social distancing]] measures in [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Bucks]], [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester]], [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware]], and [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery]] counties in the [[Philadelphia]] suburbs along with [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Allegheny County]] in the [[Pittsburgh]] area, which urges non-essential businesses to close, such as malls, movie theaters, and casinos. Essential businesses such as gas stations, grocery stores, and pharmacies will remain open. Essential services such as police, fire, and emergency medical services will be available. Starting March 16, bars and restaurants will be ordered to close to dine-in customers in those counties. Starting March 17, [[Fine Wine & Good Spirits]] stores in the four suburban Philadelphia counties will close. In addition, non-essential travel is discouraged. A no visitor policy was implemented for correctional facilities and nursing homes statewide.<ref name=6abc31520>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus PA: State announces 16 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to at least 63 across the commonwealth|publisher=WPVI-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=March 15, 2020|url=https://6abc.com/health/pennsylvania-announces-16-new-confirmed-covid-19-cases/6015347/|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316130659/https://6abc.com/health/pennsylvania-announces-16-new-confirmed-covid-19-cases/6015347/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Philadelphia Mayor Jim Kenney issued a [[stay-at-home order]] for the city, set to take effect the following day at 8:00 am.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gammage |first1=Jeff |title=Philadelphia issues 'stay at home' order; Wolf says shutdowns could last longer as pandemic grows |url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/stay-at-home-order-kenney-covid-19-coronavirus-wolf-murphy-20200323.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On Monday the 23rd, Governor Wolf issued additional stay at home orders for seven counties: Allegheny, Bucks, Chester, Delaware, Montgomery, Monroe, and a redundant order for Philadelphia County, to go into effect at 8:00 pm the same day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coloumbis |first1=Angela |last2=McDaniel |first2=Justine |title=Pa. Gov. Tom Wolf extends school closures until early April, issues stay-at-home order for 7 counties |url=https://www.spotlightpa.org/news/2020/03/pennsylvania-coronavirus-stay-at-home-order-tom-wolf/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=Spotlight PA |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*On March 16, the social distancing measures were extended to the entire state, while Philadelphia Mayor [[Jim Kenney]] ordered nonessential businesses and city government to close for two weeks.<ref name=6abc31620>{{cite news|title=Governor Wolf extends COVID-19 shutdown across Pennsylvania|publisher=WPVI-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://6abc.com/health/governor-extends-covid-19-shutdown-across-pa-live/6018275/|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Starting March 17, [[SEPTA Regional Rail]] trains in the Philadelphia area will operate on an enhanced Saturday schedule for two weeks due to reduced ridership and staffing. In addition, [[SEPTA]] will offer refunds for unused and partially used passes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Madej|first=Patricia|title=SEPTA adjusts Regional Rail schedules amid coronavirus, offers some refunds for riders|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/septa-regional-rail-schedules-coronavirus-fare-refund-credit-20200316.html|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316235343/https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/septa-regional-rail-schedules-coronavirus-fare-refund-credit-20200316.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On March 19, the state's [[Pennsylvania Department of Education|department of education]] announced that all statewide assessments would be canceled for the remainder of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc27.com/news/local/pa-department-of-education-cancels-statewide-assessments/|title=Pa. Department of Education cancels statewide assessments|date=2020-03-19|website=ABC27|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319214508/https://www.abc27.com/news/local/pa-department-of-education-cancels-statewide-assessments/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On March 22, Governor Tom Wolf announced the commonwealth would likely postpone its [[2020 Pennsylvania Democratic primary|Democratic]] and Republican primary elections from April 28 to June 2.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lai |first1=Jonathan |last2=Brennan |first2=Chris |last3=Angela |first3=Couloumbis |title=Pennsylvania governor, legislative leaders reach deal to postpone 2020 primary for coronavirus |url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/pennsylvania-postpone-2020-primary-election-coronavirus-20200323.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=Philadelphia Inquirer |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323042839/https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/pennsylvania-postpone-2020-primary-election-coronavirus-20200323.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]] and [[2020 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019-20 Pittsburgh Penguins season|Pittsburgh Penguins]] and [[2019\u201320 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=March 14, 2020 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=March 12, 2020 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=March 18, 2020 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases in Pennsylvania<ref name=\":0\" />\nUpdated April 12, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adams County, Pennsylvania|Adams]]\n|56\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Allegheny]]\n|876\n|21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Armstrong County, Pennsylvania|Armstrong]]\n|28\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Beaver County, Pennsylvania|Beaver]]\n|153\n|13\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bedford County, Pennsylvania|Bedford]]\n|5\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Berks County, Pennsylvania|Berks]]\n|1,150\n|21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Blair County, Pennsylvania|Blair]]\n|11\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bradford County, Pennsylvania|Bradford]]\n|19\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Bucks]]\n|1,177\n|36\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Butler County, Pennsylvania|Butler]]\n|143\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cambria County, Pennsylvania|Cambria]]\n|14\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cameron County, Pennsylvania|Cameron]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Carbon County, Pennsylvania|Carbon]]\n|102\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Centre County, Pennsylvania|Centre]]\n|70\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester]]\n|593\n|17\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clarion County, Pennsylvania|Clarion]]\n|16\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clearfield County, Pennsylvania|Clea